	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=73658><span id=Sage>DavivMcD</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>300 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good [4.18]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Quote: &quot;Having uber gear is pretty much the goal of the game.&quot;<br><br>Why do people like you play this game? To get &quot;uber&quot; gear? Well, if you wanna pay $12 a month just so you can work day and night on a character that doesn't exist, so you can collect fabulous and powerful treasure that doesn't exist, be my guest. In my opinion, the only thing that makes EQ worth playing and worth paying is the fact that you're playing with thousands of other usually friendly people. If you don't agree, think about the last time you talked to anyone, grouped with anyone, done a deal with anyone, saw anyone, heard anyone, or got any money or equipment you didn't loot from a mob you soloed or received from a quest. Now erase all those moments and think where you would be now if EQ was a single player game. So don't act like it's a single player game. The point of the game, and any game, is to HAVE FUN, not to beat it. Jeez, you can't even beat EQ, so why would the &quot;goal&quot; be to get uber equipment?&nbsp;&nbsp;<br><br>I sorta chuckle at your childish insult of &quot;the lowbies&quot;. Now I know who it really is that camps orc camps with his level 59 and when the lower levels complain you say &quot;I own you, stupid noobs! I am one lewt dewd!!!&quot; Do you realize that there are real people playing those characters, and that one of those newbs could already have 3 level 60s, or maybe that one of those real people could be smarter, wiser, and/or more worthy of respect than you? The highest level and uberest characters in EQ are played by people who spend so much time in EQ that they have no real life. I've been playing EQ for over a year and a half, and I only have a level 32 with crappy equipment to show for it. I don't care that I'm not level 60 with uber stuff yet because I don't need phat lewt to have fun, and at the same time I played EQ I've managed to keep my real life in better shape than it's ever been before.<br><br>Quote: &quot;To me it seems until you have played all aspects of the game you should stick to talking about what you know&quot;<br><br>I AM sticking to what I know: the low to mid-end game. All my arguments are why you shouldn't twink AT LOW LEVELS. I don't give a crap what the end-game is like because a) That's not all there is to the game, b) No end to the game actually exists, and c) Many if not most people will never even see the &quot;end&quot;-game, like me.<br><br>That is the major problem with EQ. It absolutely does NOT cater to the casal player; just to the hard-core, middle-aged, lives in his parents' basement player. The casual player is caught up in the excitement of EQ, but as they continue to play they must either devote more of their life to EQ and less to real life, or just get frustrated and stop playing. I fall into this second category. I haven't played EQ in 3 months, and I don't miss it. I'm looking forward to WoW mainly cuz Blizzard (IMHO the greatest game company ever) is gonna take all the MMORPG's, take the good stuff, fix the bad stuff, and add in their own originality into it.<br><br>Sorry I go off topic a lot but a word about Blizzard: Why do people criticize Blizzard so much about hackers? They ship out an excellent game for a one-time price, and throw in Battle.net for free. Battle.net automatically updates your game to the latest version, protects against hackers (not complete protection but a lot better than you think), and is one of the best utilities for chatting and guilding and grouping and playing in an easy and user-friendly manner, all FOR FREE. If you can give me an example of any other best-selling multiplayer games out there that isn't a victim of hackers, please let me know. Oh and MMORPG's like EQ DON'T count. First of all everything you could possibly alter to cheat is on Verant's computers, not your own. It's one thing to take a hex editor and change a couple numbers in a character file on your computer, but it's infinitely harder to do the same to a file on a highly secure network without being detected. Second, there is a monthly fee to play MMORPG's, which is what funds the security that keeps their files safe. Now if idiots using hacks they downloaded off the internet is the only thing that makes you decide you don't like Blizzard, then what'll happen when Blizzard eliminates the hacker factor? The greatest game for years to come, I hope.</p>&nbsp;<br>Daviv McD (Un-retired!)<br>36th Dwarf Rogue<br>Fury Fighters<br>Xegony<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=13233" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=13233</a></td></td></tr>
